<article>
			<h1 class=3D"posttitle" id=3D"post-95"><a href=3D"https://library.fangra=
phs.com/offense/obp/" rel=3D"bookmark" title=3D"Permanent link to OBP">OBP<=
/a></h1>
		=09
				<div class=3D"postmeta">=20
					<div class=3D"postmeta_author">by <a href=3D"https://library.fangraphs=
.com/author/steve-slow/" title=3D"Posts by Piper Slowinski" rel=3D"author">=
Piper Slowinski</a>=20
												</div>
					<div>February 16, 2010</div>
				</div>=09

			<div class=3D"fullpostentry">
			<p><em>On-Base Percentage (OBP)</em> measures the most important thing a=
 batter can do at the plate: not make an out. Since a team only gets 27 out=
s per game, making outs at a high rate isn=E2=80=99t a good thing =E2=80=94=
 that is, if a team wants to win. Players with high on-base percentages avo=
id making outs and reach base at a high rate, prolonging games and giving t=
heir team more opportunities to score.</p>
<p><span style=3D"text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Calculation:</strong=
></span></p>
<p>The formula for OBP is simple:</p>
<p style=3D"text-align: center;"><img decoding=3D"async" class=3D"alignnone=
 size-full wp-image-1513" title=3D"OBP Formula" src=3D"http://www.fangraphs=
.com/library/wp-content/uploads/2010/02/wOBA-Formula.png" alt=3D"" width=3D=
"287" height=3D"43"></p>
<p>Generally, you can swap out the denominator for PA without much issue, b=
ut little things like sacrifice bunts and catcher=E2=80=99s interference ar=
en=E2=80=99t included so it won=E2=80=99t be perfectly equivalent.</p>
<p><strong><span style=3D"text-decoration: underline;">Why OBP:</span></str=
ong></p>
<p>OBP was a big leap forward ten or twenty years ago because it gave credi=
t to hitters who reached base via walk or HBP when batting average ignored =
those things. Any time you don=E2=80=99t make an out, you=E2=80=99re contri=
buting positively to the run scoring process and OBP captures that better t=
han batting average because it incorporates a big slice of offensive activi=
ty that batting average doesn=E2=80=99t consider. Getting on base via walk =
doesn=E2=80=99t help your team quite as much as getting a hit, but it=E2=80=
=99s certainly valuable enough to warrant inclusion in even the most simpli=
stic metrics.</p>
<p>OBP has become synonymous&nbsp;with the book =E2=80=9CMoneyball=E2=80=9D=
 because at in the early 2000s, teams weren=E2=80=99t properly valuing play=
ers with high OBPs and the Oakland A=E2=80=99s could swipe talented players=
 for cheap because they were one of the few teams paying attention to walk =
rate. These days, every team has come to accept how vitally important OBP i=
s to their success, and that particular =E2=80=9Cmarket inefficiency=E2=80=
=9D has been closed.</p>
<p><strong><span style=3D"text-decoration: underline;">How to Use OBP:</spa=
n></strong></p>
<p>OBP reads like batting average, but because it incorporates walks, OBPs =
are about 60 points higher on average. So the equivalent of a .300 hitter s=
hould have a .360 OBP or so.</p>
<p>Getting on base is an important skill, so you want to use OBP to determi=
ne if the player in question is a good offensive performer. However, OBP ca=
n only take you so far and it should only be used in the context of other s=
tatistics because OBP weights every time you reach base equally, whether yo=
u hit a home run or an infield single. If used in conjunction with slugging=
 percentage or isolated slugging percentage, OBP is a very useful tool. In =
general, something like wOBA or wRC+ will tell a more accurate story, but i=
f you=E2=80=99re looking for something extremely simple OBP is a much bette=
r bet than batting average.</p>
<p><span style=3D"text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Context:</strong></s=
pan></p>
<p>Please note that the following chart is meant as an estimate, and that l=
eague-average OBP varies on a year-by-year basis. To see the league-average=
 OBP for every year from 1901 to the present, <a href=3D"http://www.fangrap=
hs.com/leaders.aspx?pos=3Dall&amp;stats=3Dbat&amp;lg=3Dall&amp;qual=3D0&amp=
;type=3D8&amp;season=3D2014&amp;month=3D0&amp;season1=3D1901&amp;ind=3D0&am=
p;team=3D0,ss&amp;rost=3D0&amp;players=3D0&amp;sort=3D0,d" target=3D"_blank=
">check the FanGraphs leaderboards</a>.</p>
<p><span style=3D"font-size: large;"><b>Rules of Thumb</b></span></p>
<table border=3D"1" width=3D"100%" cellspacing=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0" alig=
n=3D"center">
